<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="218" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,511,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="218">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,836,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="218">Comments.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[341,594,836,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="218" refString="Modarres Awal, M. (1997) Bruchidae. In: Modarres Awal, M. (Ed.), List of agricultural pests and their natural enemies in Iran. Ferdowsi University Press, Mashhad, pp. 130 - 131." type="book chapter">Modarres Awal (1997)</bibRefCitation>
reported apple, cherry, horary cress, morning glory, and pear as the hosts of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,270,872,896]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Spermophagus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericeus">
<emphasis box="[151,270,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="218">S. sericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In 
<taxonomicName box="[313,428,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Bruchinae">Bruchinae</taxonomicName>
many adults feed on various flowers but as true hosts we consider only those plant species where in seeds larvae develop.
</paragraph>
